At the close of the last period, the public time stood at 7:51 p.m. It ends this week at the same mark, with a net change of zero minutes. Underneath that still surface, many traits move: executive power without effective oversight, law as a weapon, policy driven by money, citizenship stratified by origin and ideology, universities and media pressed into line. The clock holds because these shifts extend and entrench an already dangerous configuration rather than crossing a new threshold. Courts block some of the most extreme moves, and the basic machinery of elections and legislation continues to run. But the direction of travel is clear. The system is still formally democratic, yet more of its weight now rests on partisan will, elite wealth, and fear.\
