The central development of Week 18 is the House\'92s passage of the \'93One Big Beautiful Bill,\'94 a reconciliation megabill that fuses tax policy, social spending, immigration enforcement, and even judicial powers into a single partisan package. After days of internal bargaining, late\uc0\u8209 night hearings, and a 1 a.m. procedural vote, Republicans push the bill through the House by a single vote, 215\'96214. The bill makes permanent or extends the 2017 tax cuts that favor corporations and the very wealthy, while phasing out modest benefits for working\u8209 class families by 2028. It shortens Affordable Care Act enrollment, imposes Medicaid work requirements, and allows enhanced premium credits to expire, with the Congressional Budget Office and independent models projecting that between 10 and 14 million more people will be uninsured by 2034. It cuts Supplemental Nutrition Assistance Program benefits by roughly 30 percent, the largest reduction in the program\'92s history, stripping about $300 billion from food aid and affecting more than 40 million people, including children and seniors.\
