To offset the revenue lost to tax cuts, the bill slashes Medicaid, SNAP, and other safety\uc0\u8209 net programs, and it triggers automatic Medicare cuts under the PAYGO law, capped at 4 percent but still totaling nearly $500 billion over seven years. Analyses from the CBO, the Committee for a Responsible Federal Budget, and the Penn Wharton Budget Model converge: the bill adds between $2.3 and $3.4 trillion to the deficit over a decade, with some estimates higher, while shifting after\u8209 tax income upward. House leaders frame the package as relief for workers, pointing to provisions like \'93no tax on tips,\'94 yet the modeling shows that people earning under about $51,000 see their after\u8209 tax income fall once lost health coverage and higher costs are counted, while the top 0.1 percent enjoy large gains. Policy here is not neutral arithmetic. It is a choice to treat inequality as a feature rather than a flaw.\
