The bill also reaches beyond taxes and benefits into the architecture of enforcement and law. It allocates tens of billions for border wall construction and mass deportation facilities, doubles the budgets of Customs and Border Protection and Immigration and Customs Enforcement, and raises ICE detention capacity to at least 100,000 people at a time. It imposes steep new fees on asylum seekers and sponsors of unaccompanied minors, turning access to legal protection into a pay\uc0\u8209 to\u8209 enter system. In a quieter but telling move, it includes provisions to restrict federal courts\'92 ability to enforce contempt citations against officials who defy orders, narrowing one of the judiciary\'92s core tools for checking executive noncompliance. The House Rules Committee advances this 1,100\u8209 page bill after a 22\u8209 hour hearing, with little time for members or the public to absorb its full reach. In this, Congress functions less as a deliberative body than as a vehicle for a pre\u8209 written agenda, with reconciliation rules used to bypass the need for broad consent.\
